      "A reliable structure is: greeting + name + one specific memory + one practical wish. Keep it under 3-4 lines for WhatsApp readability. Long messages can work for very close people, but they should still be structured. If you want long form, call them. If you want message impact, keep it sharp.",
      "## Rule 3: Time Your Message Like You Mean It",
      "Timing matters more than wording quality in many cases. Sending at 5:00 AM may get ignored unless you know the recipient is up. Sending too late at night feels like obligation cleanup. Best windows are usually mid-morning and early evening local time. For international contacts, send in their time zone, not yours. This tiny adjustment makes your message feel intentional.",
      "Also avoid midnight pile-ons unless the relationship expects it. Midnight works for birthdays in close circles, but festival greetings are generally less time-sensitive. A calm, thoughtful message at 9:30 AM beats a noisy midnight copy-paste blast.",
